● After CNNs (L12), your students will have: neural net foundations, training loops, embeddings (L6), transfer learning,  
  fine-tuning pretrained models. That's a strong base.                                                                    
                                                                                                                          
  The actual gaps before modern ML, ranked by importance:
                                                                                                                          
  1. Tokenization (essential, but not a full lesson)              
  Students need to understand how text becomes numbers. BPE, vocabulary size, token limits. Without this, LLM API usage
  feels like magic. 15-20 min at the start of your first LLM lesson covers it.

  2. Word/sentence embeddings (important, partially covered)
  The leap from "embed job categories" (L6) to "embed words/sentences" is the key step for RAG. Cosine similarity for
  semantic search. This probably deserves 30-40 min with hands-on code — embed some sentences, visualize clusters, search
  by similarity.

  3. The attention concept (nice to have, not blocking)
  High-level "why transformers replaced RNNs" — parallel processing, long-range dependencies, query/key/value as a lookup
  mechanism. 20 min with diagrams. Students can use LLMs effectively without understanding attention deeply.

  None of these justify a full lesson. They're all intros that fit naturally into your modern stack lessons. The plan
  already notes this — tokenization at start of L13/L14, embeddings in L14, attention as brief historical context.

  The honest answer: nothing between CNNs and modern ML needs a dedicated lesson. Transfer learning in L12 is the real
  bridge — "use someone else's pretrained model" is the same pattern whether it's ResNet for images or GPT for text. Your
  students will already get that.

  Move to modern ML after L12. Spend your limited lessons on LLM APIs, embeddings/semantic search, RAG, and agents —
  that's where the practical value is. Weave the conceptual bridges (tokenization, attention, embedding intuition) into
  those lessons as 15-30 min intros rather than standalone content.

  Collab filtering, NLP basics, transformer architecture deep-dives — all interesting, none worth delaying the modern
  stack for.